{{Quote|Our ancestor believed that out of the universal armageddon of a new, artificially-generated Big Bang might come with a better tomorrow&hellip; Lucky for all he never became quite depressed enough to use his device, and its secrets were lost with his death&hellip;|[[Santor]]|<ref name="SW87">[[Star Wars (1977) 87|''Star Wars'' (1977) 87]]</ref>}}
[[File:Shawkenese_universe_destroyer_screen.jpg|thumb|right|150px|A screen showing a simulation of the superweapon's power.]]
The '''Shawken Device'''<ref name="Checklist">{{SWArchive|url=eu/lit/ref/f20080104/indexp11.html|text=Checklist: 10 ''Star Wars'' Superweapons - The Shawken Device}}</ref> was a weapon designed to be the most destructive [[Superweapon/Legends|superweapon]] imaginable.<ref name="SW87" />

==Description==
{{Quote|This primitive construct would ignite the universe into a conflagration or collapse it into a singularity, depending on which genre of holothriller you prefer.|[[Bevel Lemelisk]]|<ref name="Imperial Handbook">''[[Star Wars: Imperial Handbook: A Commander's Guide]]''</ref>}}
[[File:Shawkenese_universe_destroyer_theory.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The theory behind the superweapon.]]
The weapon's creator intended for it to destroy the universe, but there is no record of a successful test of any kind, nor any evidence to suggest that it was actually capable of doing so.<ref name="Checklist" /> The weapon was intended to accomplish this by destroying the planet [[Shawken]] and hurling its fragments at sublight speeds to collide with other planets, theoretically setting off a chain reaction that would eventually destroy all matter and end the universe, presumably allowing the birth of another universe.<ref name="SW87" />

==History==
{{Quote|Surprised to see this here, because I recently had a personal encounter with the Shawken Device. I switched it off and I'm happy never knowing whether it was a fake or not.|[[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] on the mention of the Shawken Device in the Imperial Handbook|<ref name="Imperial Handbook" />}}The weapon was designed by an unknown Shawkenese [[Scientist/Legends|scientist]] in the distant past. The unknown scientist who developed the weapon was an extreme nihilist, and believed that the only way to imbue purpose into existence was to destroy the current universe and trigger a new [[Big Bang]], re-creating the universe.<ref name="SW87" />

The scientist's descendant [[Santor]] pointed out that he "never became quite depressed enough to use his device," and noted that "its secrets were lost with his death." It was buried underground on Shawken and remained in obscurity for many years, until it was accidentally activated shortly after the [[Battle of Endor/Legends|Battle of Endor]] in [[4 ABY/Legends|4 ABY]], by the [[Corellian/Legends|Corellian]] con artist [[Rik Duel/Legends|Rik Duel]] and his gang; it was quickly deactivated by [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] and [[Kiro]], leaving it a matter of speculation as to whether or not the device actually worked.<ref name="SW87" />

The Empire also heard of the Shawken Device and its destructive output, noting it in the field manual for the [[Imperial Military/Legends|Imperial Military]], the ''[[Imperial Handbook: A Commander's Guide]]''. Luke Skywalker, who at the time had just stopped the device before it could trigger a new big bang, was surprised to see it mentioned in the Handbook.<ref name="Imperial Handbook" />

==Behind the scenes==
The Shawken Device was introduced in the [[1984]] comic book [[Star Wars (1977) 87|''Star Wars'' 87]], written by [[Mary Jo Duffy]] and drawn by [[Tom Palmer]].<ref name="SW87" /> The superweapon went unnamed for years until it was nicknamed by [[Pablo Hidalgo]] as the "Shawken Device" in his article ''Checklist: 10'' Star Wars ''Superweapons''.<ref name="Checklist" />

